Product Requirement Document (PRD)Project Name: Hookdown (MVP)1. Document Control & MetadataTitle: Hookdown Core Platform MVPAuthor/Owner: Israel Ojiefoh Status: Approved / In ProgressTarget Release Date: Q3 20262. Objective & Strategic AlignmentThe Problem: The African creator economy faces a fundamental trust deficit. Brands frequently complain about content creators ghosting them after receiving upfront payments. Conversely, creators frequently struggle to collect payments from brands after delivering completed campaign assets.The Vision: Hookdown eliminates this friction by serving as a secure, automated intermediary web application. It "hooks" local creators up with brands and securely "locks down" campaign budgets using a milestone-driven escrow contract engine.Business Goal: Facilitate secure B2B marketing collaborations, establish transaction velocity via local milestone funding, and capture market share by offering unmatched payment security for both parties.3. User Personas & Use CasesUser PersonasThe Creator: A young, mobile-first independent content creator looking for legitimate brand collaborations, demanding immediate, guaranteed payouts upon asset delivery.The Brand/Merchant: A local business owner, startup founder, or corporate marketing manager seeking high-quality influencer content without the financial risk of unfulfilled upfront payments.User StoriesAs a Creator, I want to see that a brand has funded a milestone before I begin production, so that I am 100% guaranteed to get paid if I fulfill the brief.As a Brand, I want my campaign funds held securely in an escrow layer until I review and approve the submitted content, so that my marketing budget is protected from creator non-performance.4. Functional RequirementsFeature List (MoSCoW Framework)Feature IDRequirement DescriptionPriorityFR-01Split Onboarding: Support Google OAuth 2.0 (primary for Creators) and Email/Password (primary for Brands) routing users to a unified mandatory role selection screen (Creator vs Brand).Must HaveFR-02Profile Management: Creators must link their local bank accounts (Account Number, Bank Name) for automated withdrawals. Brands fill out company profile parameters.Must HaveFR-03Campaign Posting: Brands can post structured briefs containing a title, guidelines, a delivery deadline, and an overall budget.Must HaveFR-04Milestone Escrow Architecture: Ability to segment campaigns into distinct milestones that can switch states (UNFUNDED $\rightarrow$ FUNDED $\rightarrow$ UNDER_REVIEW $\rightarrow$ COMPLETED).Must HaveFR-05Content Submission: Creators must be able to submit text inputs, image uploads, or external URLs directly to a funded milestone for brand review.Must HaveFR-06Real-Time Notification Infrastructure: Pushing immediate UI dashboard notifications to creators when a milestone state shifts to FUNDED.Should HaveFR-07Dispute Mitigation Trigger: A "Dispute" mechanism that halts automated fund release and flags the contract row for manual admin arbitration if criteria are unmet.Should HaveFR-08Data Exporting: Ability for Brands to export transaction and campaign expense histories to a standard CSV file.Could HaveCore User Flow (The Milestone Loop)Creation: Brand posts a campaign brief $\rightarrow$ Creator applies $\rightarrow$ Brand accepts application.The Lock: Brand pays to fund Milestone 1 $\rightarrow$ System updates state to FUNDED $\rightarrow$ Creator gets notified.Submission: Creator produces asset $\rightarrow$ Uploads URL/file to the milestone $\rightarrow$ State updates to UNDER_REVIEW.The Release: Brand reviews asset $\rightarrow$ Clicks "Approve" $\rightarrow$ System triggers local payout API route $\rightarrow$ State updates to COMPLETED.5. Non-Functional Requirements (NFRs)Performance:The web application must utilize Next.js Server-Side Rendering (SSR) for public campaign boards and creator directories to load instantly under local network environments (4G desktop routers/mobile hotspots).Client-side interactions must utilize optimistic UI updates (via TanStack Query) to display state changes immediately before server-side round-trips complete.Security & Compliance:Row-Level Security (RLS): Strict PostgreSQL RLS policies must prevent unauthorized users from viewing private financial ledger states or foreign escrow entries.All server-side environment configurations, database credentials, and payment API integrations must remain hidden within Next.js server actions / API routes.Scalability: The architecture must decouple computational logic (Next.js App Router on containerized node instances) from the data tier (Supabase PostgreSQL instance) to easily accommodate traffic spikes.6. UX & UI ReferencesWireframes/Mockups: Layouts will target clean, high-density data tables for tracking active contracts, with a minimal layout utilizing the Shadcn/ui component framework.Component Behavior:Loading States: Skeletons must be rendered natively during async data mutations to avoid layout shifts.Error Handling: Form fields must show validation states immediately via TypeScript constraints on the frontend before sending malformed inputs to Supabase.7. Success Metrics & AnalyticsPrimary Metric: Milestone Completion Velocity (The duration between a milestone shifting from FUNDED to COMPLETED).Secondary Metrics:User conversion rate on the initial role selection onboarding layout.Dispute Rate (Percentage of funded milestones resulting in an active dispute trigger).Tracking Requirements: Explicit logging of state transitions (escrow_funded, asset_submitted, milestone_released) to track transactional health.8. Out of ScopeMobile Formats: Native iOS or Android distribution packages are excluded from this phase; Hookdown V1 is purely an optimized web application (hookdown-web).Algorithmic Matchmaking: No automated machine learning recommendation engines for matching creators to briefs; discovery relies purely on structural directory filters.Automated Dispute Resolutions: AI or automated checking of deliverables against the prompt brief is excluded. All disputes flag a manual operational table.
